'''Helen Stone''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|FREng|}} <ref name="glassceiling">{{cite web|last1=Grihault|first1=Nicki|title=Breaking the glass ceiling is harder abroad|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/expat/4201030/Breaking-the-glass-ceiling-is-harder-abroad.html|website=The Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|accessdate=14 October 2014|ref=1}}</ref> is an English [[civil engineer]] and 
has held the post of managing director of [[Atkins (company)|WS Atkins]] Structural Engineering, which she joined in 1972.<ref name="wsatkins">{{cite news|title=Engineering a Career at W. S. Atkins|work=The Financial Times Historical Archive|publisher=Financial Times [London, England]|date=3 June 1994}}</ref>

She attended the [[North London Collegiate School]]<ref name="nlcs">{{cite web|title=Governing Body|url=http://www.nlcsjeju.co.kr/874/about/governing-body|website=NLCS Jeju|publisher=North London Collegiate School Jeju|accessdate=14 October 2014|ref=3}}</ref> and after becoming inspired to become a civil engineer through, in her own words, "a trip up the newly-opened M1 motorway when I was 10."<ref name="cic">{{cite web|last1=Stone|first1=Helen|title=Creating careers in the construction professions|url=http://nationaldanceawards.com/BuildVisions/index.shtml|website=Construction Industry Council|accessdate=14 October 2014|ref=4}}</ref> She studied civil engineering at the [[University of Birmingham]], obtained chartered status,<ref name="nlcs" /> and has worked on engineering projects including the [[Channel Tunnel]], motorways, a theme park, aircraft hangar and oil refinery.<ref name="nlcs" /><ref name="cic" />

In 1991 she became only the third woman to become a fellow of the [[Institution of Civil Engineers]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=CNPLUS|title=Helen Stone of WS Atkins becomes the third woman fellow of the Institute of Civil Engineers|url=http://www.cnplus.co.uk/news/23aug91-uk-helen-stone-of-ws-atkins-becomes-third-woman-fellow-of-the-institute-of-civil-engineers/1707452.article#.VD1vFfnF8qY|website=CNPLUS|publisher=Construction News|accessdate=14 October 2014}}</ref> and in 2002 she was elected a fellow of the [[Royal Academy of Engineering]].<ref>{{cite web|title=RAEng: List of Fellows|url=http://www.raeng.org.uk/about-us/people-council-committees/the-fellowship/list-of-fellows|accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref> She is known for representing British engineering overseas,<ref name="nlcs" /> and has a particular interest in representing the interests of women in engineering. According to the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name="glassceiling" /> she found that in a wide range of countries, women were not being promoted to senior positions in engineering to the same extent as men, and now chairs the Diversity Panel of the [[Construction Industry Council]].<ref name="cic" /> However, despite saying that "I am conscious that I have a responsibility to break down inappropriate barriers which prevent women engineers from making progress,"<ref name="wsatkins" /> she is not in favour of positive discrimination, believing that it could lead to a lowering of standards.<ref name="wsatkins" />

She is the Chair of the Ethics and Standards Board of the [[APM Group Ltd|APM Group]], an accreditation group.<ref>{{cite web|title=APMG International|url=https://apmg-international.com/about-us|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>

